-1 Elections Canada \u2013 Confirmed candidates for New Brunswick Southwest, 30 September 2015]</ref><ref>[http://www.elections.ca/content2.aspx?section=can&dir=cand/canlim&document=index&lang=e Elections Canada \u2013 Preliminary Election Expenses Limits for Candidates]</ref>|}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{CANelec/top|CA|2011|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|[[John Williamson (Canadian politician)|John Williamson]] |18,066|56.64|-1.68|$46,347.59}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Andrew Graham|7,413|23.24|+6.69|$7,703.67}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal| Kelly Wilson|4,320|13.54|-6.03|$25,159.26}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Janice Harvey|1,646|5.16|-0.40|$7,546.35}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Christian Heritage|Jason Farris|450|1.41|&ndash;|$2,698.60}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit|31,895|100.0 &nbsp;|&nbsp;|$81,201.04}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total rejected, unmarked and declined ballots|188|0.59|-0.01}}\n{{CANelec/total|Turnout|32,083|64.71|+3.54}}\n{{CANelec/total|Eligible voters|49,578}}\n{{CANelec/hold|CA|Conservative|-4.18}}\n{{CANelec/source|source=Sources:<ref>[http://www.elections.ca/scripts/ovr2011/default.html Elections Canada \u2013 Official voting results, Forty-first general election, 2011]</ref><ref>[http://www.elections.ca/WPAPPS/WPF/EN/CC/SelectSearchOptions?act=C2&eventid=34&returntype=1 Elections Canada \u2013 Candidate's electoral campaign return, 41st general election]</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Current Members of the Canadian House of Commons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williamson, John}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian political consultants]]\n[[Category:People from Fredericton]]\n[[Category:McGill University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Communications directors of the Canadian Prime Minister's Office]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "CGTStewart", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo, awkward wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Williamson_(Canadian_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Allen Kagina", "text_new": "{{short description|Ugandan business administrator}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Allen Kagina\n| image       =\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1961}}\n| birth_place = [[Uganda]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  = [[Makerere University]]<br/>([[Bachelor of Science|Bachelor of Science in psychology]])<br/>[[University of Liverpool]]<br/>([[Master of Public Administration]])\n| occupation                = [[Administrator (business)|Business administrator]] \n| years_active              = 1985\u2013present\n| nationality               = [[Uganda]]n\n| citizenship               = [[Uganda]]\n| residence                 = [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]\n| known_for                 = [[Administrator (business)|Administrative skills]], [[integrity]]\n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = [[Kampala]]\n| title                     = [[Executive director]]<br/>[[Uganda National Roads Authority]]\n}}\n\n'''Allen Catherine Kagina''' is a [[Uganda]]n [[administrator (business)|administrator]]. She is the [[executive director]] of the [[Uganda National Roads Authority]] (UNRA). She was appointed to that position on 27 April 2015.<ref name=\"New\">{{cite web| title=Allen Kagina To Head UNRA | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Allen-Kagina-appointed-UNRA-Executive-Director/-/688334/2698930/-/wd7k8qz/-/index.html|accessdate=27 April 2015|date=27 April 2015|newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]]| first=Nelson| last=Bwire |location=Kampala}}</ref> Before that, from 2004 until 2014, she served as the director general of the [[Uganda Revenue Authority]] (URA).<ref>{{cite web|title=More Changes In URA |newspaper=[[New Vision]] |\nurl=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1168429/changes-ura |\ndate=24 March 2007 | accessdate=20 October 2016 | first=Peter| last=Kaujju | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\nShe was born in [[Rukungiri District]], [[Western Region, Uganda|Western Region of Uganda]], in 1961 to Hezron and Catherine Kakuyo<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.softpower.ug/hezron-kakuyo-father-to-unras-allen-kagina-dies-at-93/|title=Hezron Kakuyo, Father to UNRA's Allen Kagina Dies at 93|date=2019-02-28|website=Online news from Uganda and the East African region - SoftPower News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref>.<ref>{{cite web| location=Kampala|\nurl=http://www.observer.ug/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11566:despite-its-rich-profile-rukungiri-wallows-in-poverty|title=Despite Its Rich Profile, Rukungiri Wallows In Poverty | date=2 January 2011 | first=Shifa| last=Mwesigye| accessdate=8 June 2014 | publisher=[[The Observer (Uganda)]]}}</ref> Kagina studied at [[Gayaza High School]], a prestigious, private, boarding, all-girl middle and high school. She holds a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in psychology obtained from [[Makerere University]], Uganda's oldest and largest public university. She also holds a [[Master of Public Administration]] obtained from the [[University of Liverpool]] in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Mother\">{{cite web| accessdate=13 May 2014|newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |location=Kampala| url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Prosper/-/688616/948138/-/iyfnysz/-/index.html|title=Allen The Tax Collector And Mother| first=Dorothy| last=Nakaweesi| date=29 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Work experience==\nKagina started her career in 1985 as a teaching assistant at Makerere University. She later moved to the [[President of Uganda|Office of the President]]. In 1992, she joined the URA as a senior principal revenue officer, serving in that capacity until 1998. In 2000, she was promoted to the rank of deputy commissioner for customs at URA, serving in that capacity until 2001. She was appointed commissioner general of URA in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kagina Set to Stay at Helm of Revenue Body | newspaper=[[New Vision]] | date=15 July 2010 | first=and Mark Owor | last=David Mugabe|\nurl=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1286450/kagina-set-stay-helm-revenue-body | accessdate=20 October 2016 | location=Kampala}}</ref> She is credited with improving the URA's financial performance. She was awarded the Corporate Leadership Award in February 2006, by Destiny Consult, an industry group, for turning around the performance of the tax body since her appointment to head the organization in 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1154865/kagina-leadership-award | newspaper=[[New Vision]] |date=8 February 2006|location=Kampala| first=Emmy |last=Olaki |accessdate=20 October 2016 | title=Kagina gets leadership award}}</ref> In October 2010, her contract was renewed for another three years. Her monthly salary was reported to be UGX:28 million (approximately: US$11,250).<ref>{{cite web|first=Yasiin |date=15 May 2015 |\nurl=http://mobile.monitor.co.ug/News/Highest-paid-government-officials-named/2466686-2716862-format-xhtml-fwucinz/index.html |last=Mugerwa |\ntitle=Highest paid government officials named |accessdate=20 October 2016 | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | location=Kampala}}</ref> On 27 April 2015, [[John Byabagambi]], the Ugandan Minister of Works and Transport at that time, appointed her as the executive director of the UNRA, effective 1 May 2015.<ref name=\"New\"/><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=20 October 2016| url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Allen-Kagina-to-head-UNRA/688334-2698930-di5yaq/index.html | date=27 April 2015 |title=Allen Kagina to head UNRA |first=Nelson |last=Bwire |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]]| location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Personal details==\nAllen Kagina is married to Paul Kagina. Together, they are the parents of three children, Dan, Michelle and Mark. She is a [[born-again Christian]].<ref name=\"Mother\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1313159/makes-allen-kagina-tick |date=25 October 2014 |title=What Makes Allen Kagina Tick |access-date=20 October 2016 |newspaper=[[New Vision]] |author=Samuel Sanya |location=Kampala}}</ref>. She is also the sister of [[Lorna Magara]], Jocelyn Kyobutungi Rugunda (wife to Uganda's Prime Minister, [[Ruhakana Rugunda]]) as well as Caleb Kakuyo (former Chief Commercial Officer at National Housing and Construction Corporation) among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freewebhostinguganda.com/ugandapressreview/kakuyo-the-fallen-hero-who-left-an-indelible-legacy/ |title=Kakuyo the fallen hero who left an indelible legacy |publisher=Uganda Press Review\u00ae |date=22 February 2019 |access-date=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of wealthiest people in Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110611004840/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/13/757011 URA Targets UGX:6.3 Trillion (US$2.7 Billion) Revenue In Financial Year:2011/2012]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kagina, Allen}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Rukungiri District]]\n[[Category:People from Western Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Ugandan Christians]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women business executives]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gayaza High School]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ugandan business administrator}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Allen Kagina\n| image       =\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth year and age|1961}}\n| birth_place = [[Uganda]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater  = '''[[Makerere University]]'''<br/>{{small|([[Bachelor of Science|Bachelor of Science in Psychology]])}}<br/>'''[[University of Liverpool]]'''<br/>{{small|([[Masters of Public Administration]])}}\n| occupation                = [[Administrator (business)|Business Administrator]] \n| years_active              = 1985 \u2014 present\n| nationality               = [[Uganda]]n\n| citizenship               = [[Uganda]]\n| residence                 = [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]\n| known_for                 = [[Administrator (business)|Administrative Skills]], [[Integrity]]\n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = [[Kampala]]\n| title                     = '''[[Executive Director]]'''<br/>[[Uganda National Roads Authority]]\n}}\n\n'''Allen Catherine Kagina''' is a [[Uganda]]n [[administrator (business)|administrator]]. She is the [[executive director]] of the [[Uganda National Roads Authority]] (UNRA). She was appointed to that position on 27 April 2015.<ref name=\"New\">{{cite web| title=Allen Kagina To Head UNRA | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Allen-Kagina-appointed-UNRA-Executive-Director/-/688334/2698930/-/wd7k8qz/-/index.html|accessdate=27 April 2015|date=27 April 2015|newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]]| first=Nelson| last=Bwire |location=Kampala}}</ref> Before that, from 2004 until 2014, she served as the director general of the [[Uganda Revenue Authority]] (URA).<ref>{{cite web|title=More Changes In URA |newspaper=[[New Vision]] |\nurl=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1168429/changes-ura |\ndate=24 March 2007 | accessdate=20 October 2016 | first=Peter| last=Kaujju | location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Background and education==\nShe was born in [[Rukungiri District]], [[Western Region, Uganda|Western Region of Uganda]], in 1961 to Hezron and Catherine Kakuyo<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.softpower.ug/hezron-kakuyo-father-to-unras-allen-kagina-dies-at-93/|title=Hezron Kakuyo, Father to UNRA's Allen Kagina Dies at 93|date=2019-02-28|website=Online news from Uganda and the East African region - SoftPower News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref>.<ref>{{cite web| location=Kampala|\nurl=http://www.observer.ug/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=11566:despite-its-rich-profile-rukungiri-wallows-in-poverty|title=Despite Its Rich Profile, Rukungiri Wallows In Poverty | date=2 January 2011 | first=Shifa| last=Mwesigye| accessdate=8 June 2014 | publisher=[[The Observer (Uganda)]]}}</ref> Kagina studied at [[Gayaza High School]], a prestigious, private, boarding, all-girl middle and high school. She holds a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in psychology obtained from [[Makerere University]], Uganda's oldest and largest public university. She also holds a [[Masters in Public Administration]] obtained from the [[University of Liverpool]] in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"Mother\">{{cite web| accessdate=13 May 2014|newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |location=Kampala| url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Prosper/-/688616/948138/-/iyfnysz/-/index.html|title=Allen The Tax Collector And Mother| first=Dorothy| last=Nakaweesi| date=29 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Work experience==\nKagina started her career in 1985 as a teaching assistant at Makerere University. She later moved to the [[President of Uganda|Office of the President]]. In 1992, she joined the URA as a senior principal revenue officer, serving in that capacity until 1998. In 2000, she was promoted to the rank of deputy commissioner for customs at URA, serving in that capacity until 2001. She was appointed commissioner general of URA in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kagina Set to Stay at Helm of Revenue Body | newspaper=[[New Vision]] | date=15 July 2010 | first=and Mark Owor | last=David Mugabe|\nurl=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1286450/kagina-set-stay-helm-revenue-body | accessdate=20 October 2016 | location=Kampala}}</ref> She is credited with improving the URA's financial performance. She was awarded the Corporate Leadership Award in February 2006, by Destiny Consult, an industry group, for turning around the performance of the tax body since her appointment to head the organization in 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1154865/kagina-leadership-award | newspaper=[[New Vision]] |date=8 February 2006|location=Kampala| first=Emmy |last=Olaki |accessdate=20 October 2016 | title=Kagina gets leadership award}}</ref> In October 2010, her contract was renewed for another three years. Her monthly salary was reported to be UGX:28 million (approximately: US$11,250).<ref>{{cite web|first=Yasiin |date=15 May 2015 |\nurl=http://mobile.monitor.co.ug/News/Highest-paid-government-officials-named/2466686-2716862-format-xhtml-fwucinz/index.html |last=Mugerwa |\ntitle=Highest paid government officials named |accessdate=20 October 2016 | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] | location=Kampala}}</ref> On 27 April 2015, [[John Byabagambi]], the Ugandan Minister of Works and Transport at that time, appointed her as the executive director of the UNRA, effective 1 May 2015.<ref name=\"New\"/><ref>{{cite web|accessdate=20 October 2016| url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/National/Allen-Kagina-to-head-UNRA/688334-2698930-di5yaq/index.html | date=27 April 2015 |title=Allen Kagina to head UNRA |first=Nelson |last=Bwire |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]]| location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n==Personal details==\nAllen Kagina is married to Paul Kagina. Together, they are the parents of three children, Dan, Michelle and Mark. She is a [[born-again Christian]].<ref name=\"Mother\"/><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1313159/makes-allen-kagina-tick |date=25 October 2014 |title=What Makes Allen Kagina Tick |access-date=20 October 2016 |newspaper=[[New Vision]] |author=Samuel Sanya |location=Kampala}}</ref>. She is also the sister of [[Lorna Magara]], Jocelyn Kyobutungi Rugunda (wife to Uganda's Prime Minister, [[Ruhakana Rugunda]]) as well as Caleb Kakuyo (former Chief Commercial Officer at National Housing and Construction Corporation) among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freewebhostinguganda.com/ugandapressreview/kakuyo-the-fallen-hero-who-left-an-indelible-legacy/ |title=Kakuyo the fallen hero who left an indelible legacy |publisher=Uganda Press Review\u00ae |date=22 February 2019 |access-date=3 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of wealthiest people in Uganda]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110611004840/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/13/757011 URA Targets UGX:6.3 Trillion (US$2.7 Billion) Revenue In Financial Year:2011/2012]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kagina, Allen}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Rukungiri District]]\n[[Category:People from Western Region, Uganda]]\n[[Category:Ugandan Christians]]\n[[Category:Ugandan women business executives]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gayaza High School]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp, cap, other cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_Kagina"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Gary\n| latin             = Dioecesis Gariensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Cathedral of the Holy Angels in Gary.jpg\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral of the Holy Angels\n| coat              = CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary.svg\n| coat_size         = 150px\n| coat_alt          = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = United States\n| territory         = The counties of [[Lake County, Indiana|Lake]], [[LaPorte County, Indiana|LaPorte]], [[Porter County, Indiana|Porter]] and [[Starke County, Indiana|Starke]] in Northwest Indiana\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of Indianapolis|Indianapolis]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 1,807<!-- Area in square miles, automatically converted -->\n| population        = 778,463\n| population_as_of  = 2006\n| catholics         = 185,550<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 23.8\n| parishes          = 73<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = 72<!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = 22<!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| sui_iuris_church  = [[Latin Church]]\n| established       = December 17, 1956 ({{age|1956|12|17}} years ago)\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of the Holy Angels (Gary, Indiana)|Cathedral of the Holy Angels]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[Guardian Angels]]<br>[[Matthias the Apostle|St. Matthias the Apostle]]\n| priests           = 105<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change --> \n| metropolitan      = \n| bishop            = [[Robert John McClory]] \n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| chancellor        =\n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Dale Joseph Melczek]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Gary map 1.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = Territory of the Diocese of Gary\n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.dcgary.org www.dcgary.org]\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Gariensis}}) is a [[particular church]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] in the United States of America. It was founded on December 17, 1956, by [[Pope Pius XII]].<ref name=\"dchis\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/bishop-history.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Bishop's Office - Brief History of the Diocese page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=dcstat /> It is one of four [[suffragan]] dioceses of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Indianapolis]]. Its ecclesiastic territory includes [[Lake County, Indiana|Lake]], [[Porter County, Indiana|Porter]], [[LaPorte County, Indiana|LaPorte]],  and [[Starke County, Indiana|Starke]] counties in northwestern [[Indiana]]. The mother church of the diocese is the [[Cathedral of the Holy Angels (Gary, Indiana)|Cathedral of the Holy Angels]] in [[Gary, Indiana]].\n\n==History==\nDuring the first half of the 20th century, many [[Catholic]] immigrants came from [[Eastern Europe]] and Mexico to work in the region's growing steel industry.<ref>{{cite book |last=Alicea |first=Marisa |editor-first=F\u00e9lix M. |editor-last=Padilla |title=Handbook of Hispanic Cultures in the United States: Sociology, Volume 3 |publisher=Arte Publico Press |date=June 1, 1994 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/sociology00kane/page/38 38] |chapter=The Latino Immigration Experience: The Case of Mexicanos, Puertorrique\u00f1os, and Cubanos |isbn=1558851011 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/sociology00kane/page/38 }}</ref> A number of parishes were founded near the steel mills so that the newly arrived immigrants could celebrate [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] in their native languages. In 1956 the four counties of [[Lake County, Indiana|Lake]], [[Porter County, Indiana|Porter]], [[LaPorte County, Indiana|LaPorte]],  and [[Starke County, Indiana|Starke]] belonged to the 18 county diocesan territory of the then named Diocese of Fort Wayne.  On December 17, 1956, the region was stunned to learn of the announcement that came from they Holy See that a new diocese was to be erected from those four counties in Northwest Indiana and the newly created Diocese of Gary came into existence.  On December 29, 1956, [[Pope Pius XII]] announced that he had named then Reverend [[Andrew Gregory Grutka]], pastor of Holy Trinity parish, to be the first bishop of the new Gary diocese.  The parish of the Holy Angels was selected to become the new cathedral for the diocese, and became the [[Cathedral of the Holy Angels (Gary, Indiana)|Cathedral of the Holy Angels]].  The new diocese, at its establishment, found itself with 129 active diocesan priests, 77 parishes, 60 parish schools and 135,485 Catholics, which was roughly 25 percent of the population of the four counties.\n\nAs of 2012, four parishes in the diocese still offered Mass in Polish, two parishes in Croatian, one in Hungarian, and one in Lithuanian. Fourteen parishes also offered Mass in Spanish. One location offered the [[Summorum Pontificum|1962 form of the Roman-Rite Mass]].<ref name=\"dcp\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/map.htm |title=Survey of individual parishes from the Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Parishes page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Diocese today==\nServing the diocese are 105 [[priesthood (Catholic Church)|priests]], 67 permanent [[deacons]], 10 [[monk|religious brothers]], and 85 [[nun|religious sisters]] who are members of various [[religious institute]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/clergy.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Clergy page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref> These priests, deacons and persons religious serve a Catholic population in [[northwest Indiana]] of 186,420<ref name=\"dcstat\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/bishop-statistics.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Bishop's Office - Gary Diocese Statistical Data page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref> in 73 [[parish]]es and missions.<ref name=dcp /><ref name=\"dcmap\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/map.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Map of Diocese page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe diocese also operates several educational, medical, and social service organizations.  Educational institutions include 17 elementary schools, 3 high schools, 1 college, and a Catholic student center at [[Valparaiso University]].<ref name=\"dcs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/catholic-schools.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Catholic Schools page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref>  The diocese also supervises six hospitals or medical centers, three homes for the aged, three protective homes, three cemeteries, and [[Catholic Charities|Catholic Charities, Diocese of Gary]].<ref name=dcmap />\n\nOn April 25, 2019, Pope Francis appointed Bishop [[Donald J. Hying]] [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Madison|Bishop of Madison]] and on November 26, 2019, [[Pope Francis]] appointed Detroit, Michigan priest [[Robert John McClory]] to succeed him.<ref name=pr20191126>{{cite press release | access-date =  November 26, 2019 | date= November 26, 2019 | publisher = Holy See Press Office | language = it | url = https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2019/11/26/0928/01912.html | title = Rinunce e Nomine, 26.09.2019 }}</ref><ref name=mcclory>https://www.wilx.com/content/news/Pope-appoints-Michigan-priest-to-be-next-bishop-of-Gary-565500852.html</ref><ref>https://www.mlive.com/news/ann-arbor/2019/11/pope-francis-appoints-detroit-priest-new-bishop-of-diocese-of-gary.html</ref> He was both consecrated and installed as Bishop on February 11, 2020.<ref name=installation>https://angelusnews.com/news/nation/pope-francis-appoints-new-bishop-of-gary-indiana/</ref>\n\n==Bishops==\n* [[Andrew Gregory Grutka]] (Appointed bishop on December 29, 1956. Retired on July 9, 1984.  Bishop Grutka died on November 11, 1993.)\n* [[Norbert Felix Gaughan]] (Appointed bishop July 9, 1984. Retired on June 1, 1996.  Bishop Gaughan died on October 1, 1999.)\n* [[Dale Joseph Melczek]] (Appointed Apostolic Administrator of the diocese on August 19, 1992 after Bishop Gaughan suffered a stroke.  Was named coadjutor bishop of the diocese on October 28, 1995. Succeeded as diocesan bishop on June 1, 1996. Retired on November 24, 2014.  He is the current bishop emeritus of the diocese.)\n* [[Donald J. Hying]] (Appointed on November 24, 2014.  He served until April 25, 2019, when he was appointed 5th Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Madison|Diocese of Madison]].)\n* [[Robert John McClory]] (Appointed bishop on November 26, 2019. Installed on February 11, 2020.)\n\n===Coadjutor Bishops===\n* [[Dale Joseph Melczek]] (October 28, 1995 to June 1, 1996)\n\n===Other diocesan priest who became bishop===\n* [[Carl Frederick Mengeling]], appointed 4th [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lansing|Bishop of Lansing]] (served as diocesan bishop from November 7, 1995 until his retirement on February 27, 2008).\n\n==Education==\nThe Superintendent of Catholic Schools is Dr. Joseph Majchrowicz, Ed.D.\n\n===Elementary schools===\nParishes run the following elementary and middle schools within the diocese:\n\n(Note: No school is in the city of Gary)\n\n*St. Patrick, Chesterton<ref>[http://www.stpatsparish.org St. Patrick Catholic Community<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. Mary Catholic Community School, Crown Point<ref>[http://www.stmarycrownpoint.org St. Mary Catholic Church<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. Stanislaus, East Chicago\n*St. Mary, Griffith<ref>[http://www.smgriffith.org St. Mary of Griffith<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. Casimir, Hammond\n*St. John Bosco, Hammond<ref>[http://www.sjb.nwiweb.com St. John Bosco - St. John Bosco - St. John Bosco parish and school in Hammond, Indiana USA<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Our Lady of Grace, Highland<ref>[http://www.olgraceschool.org Our Lady of Grace School]</ref>\n*Aquinas School at St. Andrew's, Merrillville\n*Notre Dame, Michigan City<ref>[http://www.notredameparish.net Notre Dame Catholic Church & School<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Queen of All Saints, Michigan City<ref>[http://www.qas-school.org Queen of All Saints Catholic School, Michigan City, IN<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. Stanislaus Kostka, Michigan City\n*St. Thomas More, Munster<ref>[http://www.stm-school.com St. Thomas More Elementary School | Munster, IN<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Nativity of Our Savior, Portage<ref>[http://www.nativitystars.info]</ref>\n*St. John the Evangelist, St. John<ref>[http://www.sjeschool.org]</ref>\n*St. Michael, Schererville<ref>[http://www.saintmichaelscher.org]</ref>\n*St. Paul Catholic, Valparaiso<ref>[http://www.stpaulvalpo.org Saint Paul Catholic School<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. John the Baptist, Whiting<ref>[http://www.sjbcatholicparish.org]</ref>\n\nSt. Catherine of Siena, a Catholic elementary school in Hammond, opened prior to 1949<!-- \"has been open for more than 50 years\" and 2009 - 50 = 1949 -->. Prior to 2009 its enrollment had declined, with 130 students that year, and its financial state had deteriorated. The school closed in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author=McCollum, Carmen|url=https://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/students-staff-parents-mourn-closing-of-longtime-catholic-school/article_748d472e-042b-571b-ac9f-b950543e8af5.html|title=Students, staff, parents mourn closing of longtime Catholic school|work=[[NWI Times]]|date=2009-05-30|accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n===Secondary schools===\n\n====Operated by Diocese====\n*[[Bishop Noll Institute]]<ref>[http://www.bishopnoll.org Home - Bishop Noll Institute<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n*[[Andrean High School]]<ref>[http://www.andreanhs.com Andrean High School | Christ is my Teacher<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*[[Marquette Catholic High School (Michigan City, Indiana)|Marquette Catholic High School]]<ref>[http://www.marquette-hs.org]</ref>\n\n====Independent====\n*[[Sacred Heart Apostolic School]]\n*[[La Lumiere School]]\n\n===Colleges===\n*[[Calumet College of St. Joseph]]<ref>[http://www.ccsj.edu CCSJ<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Extraordinary Form==\n{{as of|2017|August}}, the only Mass in the [[Extraordinary Form of the Roman Rite]] in the diocese is offered at the Carmelite Shrine in [[Munster, Indiana|Munster]] on Saturday evenings. It was established on Saturday, August 25, 1990, at the recommendation of Bishop [[Norbert Felix Gaughan|Norbert Gaughan]]. The Mass was featured in newspapers across the country when ''[[Summorum Pontificum]]'' was promulgated by [[Pope Benedict XVI]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Mass Fills Pews at Munster Monastery|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/latin-mass-fills-pews-at-munster-monastery/article_503498b7-9521-5e80-9452-c3dda14a7ead.html|publisher=NWI Times|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nPreviously, a Traditional Latin Mass was available at St. Stanislaus in [[Michigan City, Indiana|Michigan City]] on Sundays, but this Mass was discontinued when the celebrant died.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Diocese Latin Mass|url=https://nwilatin.org/about|website=NWI Latin Mass Community|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> St. Joseph the Worker in Gary had a monthly Mass that was a hybrid of the Extraordinary and Ordinary Forms.{{clarify|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn 2015, the NWI Latin Mass Community was founded by laity to support and promote the Extraordinary Form in the Gary Diocese, with the particular goals of offering Sunday morning and Holy Day Masses in the Extraordinary Form, as well as fostering parish life for those who are attached to the older form of the Mass.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nOn January 1, 2018, a Solemn High Mass was offered at the [[Cathedral of the Holy Angels (Gary, Indiana)|Cathedral of the Holy Angels]] by Bishop [[Joseph Perry (bishop)|Joseph Perry]]{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}, auxiliary bishop for the Archdiocese of Chicago.\n\nIn 2018, the [[Institute of Christ the King Sovereign Priest|Institute of Christ the King]] began an apostolate at St. Joseph parish in Hammond, offering the Extraordinary Form on a weekly basis. St. Joseph parish in Dyer also holds a monthly mass in the Extraordinary Form.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|Indiana|Chicago|Catholicism}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States#Ecclesiastical province of Indianapolis|Ecclesiastical Province of Indianapolis]]\n* [[Global organisation of the Catholic Church]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic archdioceses]] (by country and continent)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (alphabetical)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (structured view)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.dcgary.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary]\n*[http://www.nwicatholic.com  NWI Catholic] (Diocese of Gary's weekly newspaper)\n*[https://www.nwilatin.org  NWI Latin Mass Community]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Indianapolis}}\n{{coord|41|34|51|N|87|20|44|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary| ]]\n[[Category:Culture of Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Dioceses in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 20th century|Gary]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Gary]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Gary\n| latin             = Dioecesis Gariensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Cathedral of the Holy Angels in Gary.jpg\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral of the Holy Angels\n| coat              = CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary.svg\n| coat_size         = 150px\n| coat_alt          = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = United States\n| territory         = The counties of [[Lake County, Indiana|Lake]], [[LaPorte County, Indiana|LaPorte]], [[Porter County, Indiana|Porter]] and [[Starke County, Indiana|Starke]] in Northwest Indiana\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of Indianapolis|Indianapolis]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 1,807<!-- Area in square miles, automatically converted -->\n| population        = 778,463\n| population_as_of  = 2006\n| catholics         = 185,550<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 23.8\n| parishes          = 73<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = 72<!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = 22<!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| sui_iuris_church  = [[Latin Church]]\n| established       = December 17, 1956 ({{age|1956|12|17}} years ago)\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of the Holy Angels (Gary, Indiana)|Cathedral of the Holy Angels]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[Guardian Angels]]<br>[[Matthias the Apostle|St. Matthias the Apostle]]\n| priests           = 105<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change --> \n| metropolitan      = \n| bishop            = [[Robert John McClory]] \n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| chancellor        =\n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Dale Joseph Melczek]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Gary map 1.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = Territory of the Diocese of Gary\n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.dcgary.org www.dcgary.org]\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Gariensis}}) is a [[particular church]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] in the United States of America. It was founded on December 17, 1956, by [[Pope Pius XII]].<ref name=\"dchis\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/bishop-history.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Bishop's Office - Brief History of the Diocese page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=dcstat /> It is one of four [[suffragan]] dioceses of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Indianapolis]]. Its ecclesiastic territory includes [[Lake County, Indiana|Lake]], [[Porter County, Indiana|Porter]], [[LaPorte County, Indiana|LaPorte]],  and [[Starke County, Indiana|Starke]] counties in northwestern [[Indiana]]. The mother church of the diocese is the [[Cathedral of the Holy Angels (Gary, Indiana)|Cathedral of the Holy Angels]] in [[Gary, Indiana]].\n\n==History==\nDuring the first half of the 20th century, many [[Catholic]] immigrants came from [[Eastern Europe]] and Mexico to work in the region's growing steel industry.<ref>{{cite book |last=Alicea |first=Marisa |editor-first=F\u00e9lix M. |editor-last=Padilla |title=Handbook of Hispanic Cultures in the United States: Sociology, Volume 3 |publisher=Arte Publico Press |date=June 1, 1994 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/sociology00kane/page/38 38] |chapter=The Latino Immigration Experience: The Case of Mexicanos, Puertorrique\u00f1os, and Cubanos |isbn=1558851011 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/sociology00kane/page/38 }}</ref> A number of parishes were founded near the steel mills so that the newly arrived immigrants could celebrate [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] in their native languages. In 1956 the four counties of [[Lake County, Indiana|Lake]], [[Porter County, Indiana|Porter]], [[LaPorte County, Indiana|LaPorte]],  and [[Starke County, Indiana|Starke]] belonged to the 18 county diocesan territory of the then named Diocese of Fort Wayne.  On December 17, 1956, the region was stunned to learn of the announcement that came from they Holy See that a new diocese was to be erected from those four counties in Northwest Indiana and the newly created Diocese of Gary came into existence.  On December 29, 1956, [[Pope Pius XII]] announced that he had named then Reverend [[Andrew Gregory Grutka]], pastor of Holy Trinity parish, to be the first bishop of the new Gary diocese.  The parish of the Holy Angels was selected to become the new cathedral for the diocese, and became the [[Cathedral of the Holy Angels (Gary, Indiana)|Cathedral of the Holy Angels]].  The new diocese, at its establishment, found itself with 129 active diocesan priests, 77 parishes, 60 parish schools and 135,485 Catholics, which was roughly 25 percent of the population of the four counties.\n\nAs of 2012, four parishes in the diocese still offered Mass in Polish, two parishes in Croatian, one in Hungarian, and one in Lithuanian. Fourteen parishes also offered Mass in Spanish. One location offered the [[Summorum Pontificum|1962 form of the Roman-Rite Mass]].<ref name=\"dcp\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/map.htm |title=Survey of individual parishes from the Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Parishes page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Diocese today==\nServing the diocese are 105 [[priesthood (Catholic Church)|priests]], 67 permanent [[deacons]], 10 [[monk|religious brothers]], and 85 [[nun|religious sisters]] who are members of various [[religious institute]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/clergy.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Clergy page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref> These priests, deacons and persons religious serve a Catholic population in [[northwest Indiana]] of 186,420<ref name=\"dcstat\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/bishop-statistics.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Bishop's Office - Gary Diocese Statistical Data page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref> in 73 [[parish]]es and missions.<ref name=dcp /><ref name=\"dcmap\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/map.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Map of Diocese page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe diocese also operates several educational, medical, and social service organizations.  Educational institutions include 17 elementary schools, 3 high schools, 1 college, and a Catholic student center at [[Valparaiso University]].<ref name=\"dcs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dcgary.org/catholic-schools.htm |title=Catholic Diocese of Gary website, Catholic Schools page, Retrieved 10 March 2012}}</ref>  The diocese also supervises six hospitals or medical centers, three homes for the aged, three protective homes, three cemeteries, and [[Catholic Charities|Catholic Charities, Diocese of Gary]].<ref name=dcmap />\n\nOn April 25, 2019, Pope Francis appointed Bishop [[Donald J. Hying]] [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Madison|Bishop of Madison]] and on November 26, 2019, [[Pope Francis]] appointed Detroit, Michigan priest [[Robert John McClory]] to succeed him.<ref name=pr20191126>{{cite press release | access-date =  November 26, 2019 | date= November 26, 2019 | publisher = Holy See Press Office | language = it | url = https://press.vatican.va/content/salastampa/it/bollettino/pubblico/2019/11/26/0928/01912.html | title = Rinunce e Nomine, 26.09.2019 }}</ref><ref name=mcclory>https://www.wilx.com/content/news/Pope-appoints-Michigan-priest-to-be-next-bishop-of-Gary-565500852.html</ref><ref>https://www.mlive.com/news/ann-arbor/2019/11/pope-francis-appoints-detroit-priest-new-bishop-of-diocese-of-gary.html</ref> He was both consecrated and installed as Bishop on February 11, 2020.<ref name=installation>https://angelusnews.com/news/nation/pope-francis-appoints-new-bishop-of-gary-indiana/</ref>\n\n==Bishops==\n* [[Andrew Gregory Grutka]] (Appointed bishop on December 29, 1956. Retired on July 9, 1984.  Bishop Grutka died on November 11, 1993.)\n* [[Norbert Felix Gaughan]] (Appointed bishop July 9, 1984. Retired on June 1, 1996.  Bishop Gaughan died on October 1, 1999.)\n* [[Dale Joseph Melczek]] (Appointed Apostolic Administrator of the diocese on August 19, 1992 after Bishop Gaughan suffered a stroke.  Was named coadjutor bishop of the diocese on October 28, 1995. Succeeded as diocesan bishop on June 1, 1996. Retired on November 24, 2014.  He is the current bishop emeritus of the diocese.)\n* [[Donald J. Hying]] (Appointed on November 24, 2014.  He served until April 25, 2019, when he was appointed 5th Bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Madison|Diocese of Madison]].)\n* [[Robert John McClory]] (Appointed bishop on November 26, 2019. Installed on February 11, 2020.)\n\n===Coadjutor Bishops===\n* [[Dale Joseph Melczek]] (October 28, 1995 to June 1, 1996)\n\n===Other diocesan priest who became bishop===\n* [[Carl Frederick Mengeling]], appointed 4th [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lansing|Bishop of Lansing]] (served as diocesan bishop from November 7, 1995 until his retirement on February 27, 2008).\n\n==Education==\nThe Superintendent of Catholic Schools is Dr. Joseph Majchrowicz, Ed.D.\n\n===Elementary schools===\nParishes run the following elementary and middle schools within the diocese:\n\n(Note: No school is in the city of Gary)\n\n*St. Patrick, Chesterton<ref>[http://www.stpatsparish.org St. Patrick Catholic Community<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. Mary Catholic Community School, Crown Point<ref>[http://www.stmarycrownpoint.org St. Mary Catholic Church<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. Stanislaus, East Chicago\n*St. Mary, Griffith<ref>[http://www.smgriffith.org St. Mary of Griffith<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. Casimir, Hammond\n*St. John Bosco, Hammond<ref>[http://www.sjb.nwiweb.com St. John Bosco - St. John Bosco - St. John Bosco parish and school in Hammond, Indiana USA<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Our Lady of Grace, Highland<ref>[http://www.olgraceschool.org Our Lady of Grace School]</ref>\n*Aquinas School at St. Andrew's, Merrillville\n*Notre Dame, Michigan City<ref>[http://www.notredameparish.net Notre Dame Catholic Church & School<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Queen of All Saints, Michigan City<ref>[http://www.qas-school.org Queen of All Saints Catholic School, Michigan City, IN<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. Stanislaus Kostka, Michigan City\n*St. Thomas More, Munster<ref>[http://www.stm-school.com St. Thomas More Elementary School | Munster, IN<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*Nativity of Our Savior, Portage<ref>[http://www.nativitystars.info]</ref>\n*St. John the Evangelist, St. John<ref>[http://www.sjeschool.org]</ref>\n*St. Michael, Schererville<ref>[http://www.saintmichaelscher.org]</ref>\n*St. Paul Catholic, Valparaiso<ref>[http://www.stpaulvalpo.org Saint Paul Catholic School<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*St. John the Baptist, Whiting<ref>[http://www.sjbcatholicparish.org]</ref>\n\nSt. Catherine of Siena, a Catholic elementary school in Hammond, opened prior to 1949<!-- \"has been open for more than 50 years\" and 2009 - 50 = 1949 -->. Prior to 2009 its enrollment had declined, with 130 students that year, and its financial state had deteriorated. The school closed in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|author=McCollum, Carmen|url=https://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/students-staff-parents-mourn-closing-of-longtime-catholic-school/article_748d472e-042b-571b-ac9f-b950543e8af5.html|title=Students, staff, parents mourn closing of longtime Catholic school|work=[[NWI Times]]|date=2009-05-30|accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n===Secondary schools===\n\n====Operated by Diocese====\n*[[Bishop Noll Institute]]<ref>[http://www.bishopnoll.org Home - Bishop Noll Institute<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n*[[Andrean High School]]<ref>[http://www.andreanhs.com Andrean High School | Christ is my Teacher<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*[[Marquette Catholic High School (Michigan City, Indiana)|Marquette Catholic High School]]<ref>[http://www.marquette-hs.org]</ref>\n\n====Independent====\n*[[Sacred Heart Apostolic School]]\n*[[La Lumiere School]]\n\n===Colleges===\n*[[Calumet College of St. Joseph]]<ref>[http://www.ccsj.edu CCSJ<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Extraordinary Form==\n{{as of|2017|August}}, the only Mass in the [[Extraordinary Form of the Roman Rite]] in the diocese is offered at the Carmelite Shrine in [[Munster, Indiana|Munster]] on Saturday evenings. It was established on Saturday, August 25, 1990, at the recommendation of Bishop [[Norbert Felix Gaughan|Norbert Gaughan]]. The Mass was featured in newspapers across the country when ''[[Summorum Pontificum]]'' was promulgated by [[Pope Benedict XVI]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Latin Mass Fills Pews at Munster Monastery|url=http://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/latin-mass-fills-pews-at-munster-monastery/article_503498b7-9521-5e80-9452-c3dda14a7ead.html|publisher=NWI Times|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nPreviously, a Traditional Latin Mass was available at St. Stanislaus in [[Michigan City, Indiana|Michigan City]] on Sundays, but this Mass was discontinued when the celebrant died.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gary Diocese Latin Mass|url=https://nwilatin.org/about|website=NWI Latin Mass Community|accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> St. Joseph the Worker in Gary had a monthly Mass that was a hybrid of the Extraordinary and Ordinary Forms.{{clarify|date=April 2018}}\n\nIn 2015, the NWI Latin Mass Community was founded by laity to support and promote the Extraordinary Form in the Gary Diocese, with the particular goals of offering Sunday morning and Holy Day Masses in the Extraordinary Form, as well as fostering parish life for those who are attached to the older form of the Mass.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nOn January 1, 2018, a Solemn High Mass was offered at the [[Cathedral of the Holy Angels (Gary, Indiana)|Cathedral of the Holy Angels]] by Bishop [[Joseph Perry (bishop)|Joseph Perry]]{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}, auxiliary bishop for the Archdiocese of Chicago.\n\nIn 2018, the [[Institute of Christ the King Sovereign Priest|Institute of Christ the King]] began an apostolate at St. Joseph parish in Hammond, offering the Extraordinary Form on a weekly basis. St. Joseph parish in Dyer also holds a monthly mass in the Extraordinary Form.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|Indiana|Chicago|Catholicism}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States#Ecclesiastical province of Indianapolis|Ecclesiastical Province of Indianapolis]]\n* [[Global organisation of the Catholic Church]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic archdioceses]] (by country and continent)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (alphabetical)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (structured view)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.dcgary.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary]\n*[http://www.nwicatholic.com  NWI Catholic] (Diocese of Gary's weekly newspaper)\n*[https://www.nwilatin.org  NWI Latin Mass Community]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Indianapolis}}\n{{coord|41|34|51|N|87|20|44|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Gary| ]]\n[[Category:Culture of Gary, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Dioceses in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 20th century|Gary]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Gary]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Gary"}
